nical authors like Geoffrey Chaucer and Edmund Spenser to less studied figures, such as printer William Copland, Elizabethan scribe Edward Banister and seventeenth-century poet and romance enthusiast, John Lane. In uniting a wide range of romance readers’ perspectives, the book complicates clear ruptures between manuscript and print, Catholic and Protestant, or medieval and Renaissance. Difficult pasts reveals how the romance book offers a new way to understand the simultaneous change and continuity that defines post-Reformation England.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aReformation in literature. 0aReligion and literaturezEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aRomances, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEdmund Spencer.  aGeoffrey Chaucer.  aantiquarianism.  abook history.  acultural memory studies.  amedieval romance.  amedievalism.  aperiodisation.  aprotestant reformation.  areception studies.1 aEnsley, Mimi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615790440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526157904423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526157904/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles